{"title_page": "Prajwal Parajuly", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Prajwal Parajuly\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], India\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| known_for          = ''[[The Gurkha's Daughter|The Gurkha's Daughter: Stories]]'', ''[[Land Where I Flee]]''\n| education          = [[Kellogg College, Oxford]]\n| occupation         = Author\n| title              = \n| school             = \n| party              = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Prajwal Parajuly''' (n\u00e9 Sharma) (born 24 October 1984) is an [[India]]n author whose works focus on [[Nepali language|Nepali]]-speaking people and their [[Nepali culture|culture]]. Parajuly's works include the short-story collection ''[[The Gurkha's Daughter]]'' and novel ''[[Land Where I Flee]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nParajuly grew up in the [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]] region of northeastern India. His father is Indian Nepali and his mother Nepalese.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kirksvilledailyexpress.com/newsnow/x787552944/Truman-grad-sharing-book-deal-experience-with-community|title=Truman grad sharing book deal experience with community|newspaper=The Kirksville Daily Express|date=2012-04-17|accessdate=2012-04-18}}</ref> He was educated at [[Truman State University]] in [[Kirksville, Missouri]], and the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitaab.org/2013/11/30/prajwal-parajuly-land-where-i-flee-is-in-many-ways-an-uncomfortable-novel/|title=Prajwal Parajuly: \u2018Land Where I Flee\u2019 is, in many ways, an uncomfortable novel|publisher=Kitaab|date=2013-11-30|accessdate=2013-11-30}}</ref> Before committing to a writing career, he worked as an advertising executive at ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref name=livemint>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/xvCdCondSh4E0hgiLzDcXK/Prajwal-Parajuly--The-Gurkhas-son.html|title=Prajwal Parajuly: The Gurkha's son|newspaper=LiveMint|date=2014-01-02|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn September 2011, Parajuly became the youngest Indian author to be offered a two-book, multi-country deal. He was signed by [[Quercus (publisher)|Quercus]].<ref name=livemint />\nHe published his first book in 2012: a short story collection with the title ''The Gurkha's Daughter: Stories''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jan/25/gurkhas-daughter-prajwal-parajuly-review|title=The Gurkha's daughter by Prajwal Parajuly - review|author=John Garth|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2013-01-25|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>  Describing and dramatizing the experiences of the Nepalese people and the Nepalese diaspora, his debut book was shortlisted for the 2013 [[Dylan Thomas Prize]]<ref>[http://www.swansea.ac.uk/dylan-thomas-prize/news/dylanthomasprizeshortlist2013announced.php \"Dylan Thomas Prize Shortlist 2013 Announced\"], Swansea University</ref> and longlisted for [[The Story Prize]] that same year.\nParajuly's second book, the novel ''Land Where I Flee'', came out in 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/books/booksreviews/book-review-land-where-i-flee/article1-1165086.aspx|title=Book review: Land Where I Flee|author=Manjula Narayan|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=2013-12-21|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> It was an ''Independent on Sunday'' book of the year and a ''[[Kansas City Star]]'' best book of 2015. It went on to be translated into [[Nepali language|Nepali]], [[French language|French]] and a number of Indian languages, including [[Hindi]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], and [[Odia language|Odia]].\nHe was the first writer-in-residence at The Oxford Centre for Hindu Studies in 2013. In 2016, Prajwal Parajuly was invited to be a judge for the Dylan Thomas Prize.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cain |first1=Sian |title=Dylan Thomas prize goes to Australian 'genius' Fiona McFarlane |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/10/dylan-thomas-prize-goes-to-australian-genius-fiona-mcfarlane |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nPrajwal Parajuly has written for [[The New York Times]], [[The Guardian]], the [[New Statesman]] and the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.kellogg.ox.ac.uk/discover/news/alumnus-prajwal-parajuly-invited-to-judge-the-international-dylan-thomas-prize-2017/|title=Alumnus Prajwal Parajuly invited to judge the International Dylan Thomas Prize 2017|publisher=Kellogg College|date=2016-11-07|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''[[The Gurkha's Daughter]]'', short story collection, released in December 2012.\n*''[[Land Where I Flee]]'', novel, released in December 2013.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parajuly, Prajwal}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Truman State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian people of Nepalese descent]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Kellogg College, Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Prajwal Parajuly\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_place        = [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]], India\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| known_for          = ''[[The Gurkha's Daughter|The Gurkha's Daughter: Stories]]'', ''[[Land Where I Flee]]''\n| education          = [[Kellogg College, Oxford]]\n| occupation         = Author\n| title              = \n| school             = \n| party              = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n}}\n'''Prajwal Parajuly''' (n\u00e9 Sharma) (born 24 October 1984) is an [[India]]n author whose works focus on [[Nepali language|Nepali]]-speaking people and their [[Nepali culture|culture]]. Parajuly's works include the short-story collection ''[[The Gurkha's Daughter]]'' and novel ''[[Land Where I Flee]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nParajuly grew up in the [[Gangtok]], [[Sikkim]] region of northeastern India. His father is Indian Nepali and his mother Nepalese.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kirksvilledailyexpress.com/newsnow/x787552944/Truman-grad-sharing-book-deal-experience-with-community|title=Truman grad sharing book deal experience with community|newspaper=The Kirksville Daily Express|date=2012-04-17|accessdate=2012-04-18}}</ref> He was educated at [[Truman State University]] in [[Kirksville, Missouri]], and the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kitaab.org/2013/11/30/prajwal-parajuly-land-where-i-flee-is-in-many-ways-an-uncomfortable-novel/|title=Prajwal Parajuly: \u2018Land Where I Flee\u2019 is, in many ways, an uncomfortable novel|publisher=Kitaab|date=2013-11-30|accessdate=2013-11-30}}</ref> Before committing to a writing career, he worked as an advertising executive at ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref name=livemint>{{cite news|url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/xvCdCondSh4E0hgiLzDcXK/Prajwal-Parajuly--The-Gurkhas-son.html|title=Prajwal Parajuly: The Gurkha's son|newspaper=LiveMint|date=2014-01-02|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn September 2011, Parajuly became the youngest Indian author to be offered a two-book, multi-country deal. He was signed by [[Quercus (publisher)|Quercus]].<ref name=livemint />\nHe published his first book in 2012: a short story collection with the title ''The Gurkha's Daughter: Stories''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jan/25/gurkhas-daughter-prajwal-parajuly-review|title=The Gurkha's daughter by Prajwal Parajuly - review|author=John Garth|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=2013-01-25|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>  Describing and dramatizing the experiences of the Nepalese people and the Nepalese diaspora, his debut book was shortlisted for the 2013 [[Dylan Thomas Prize]].<ref>[http://www.swansea.ac.uk/dylan-thomas-prize/news/dylanthomasprizeshortlist2013announced.php \"Dylan Thomas Prize Shortlist 2013 Announced\"], Swansea University.</ref> Parajuly's second book, the novel ''Land Where I Flee'', came out in 2013.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/books/booksreviews/book-review-land-where-i-flee/article1-1165086.aspx|title=Book review: Land Where I Flee|author=Manjula Narayan|newspaper=Hindustan Times|date=2013-12-21|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref> It was an ''Independent on Sunday'' book of the year and a ''[[Kansas City Star]]'' best book of 2015. He was the first writer-in-residence at The Oxford Centre for Hindu Studies in 2013. In 2016, Prajwal Parajuly was invited to be a judge for the Dylan Thomas Prize.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cain |first1=Sian |title=Dylan Thomas prize goes to Australian 'genius' Fiona McFarlane |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/may/10/dylan-thomas-prize-goes-to-australian-genius-fiona-mcfarlane |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for [[The New York Times]], [[The Guardian]], the [[New Statesman]] and the [[BBC]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.kellogg.ox.ac.uk/discover/news/alumnus-prajwal-parajuly-invited-to-judge-the-international-dylan-thomas-prize-2017/|title=Alumnus Prajwal Parajuly invited to judge the International Dylan Thomas Prize 2017|publisher=Kellogg College|date=2016-11-07|accessdate=2018-07-20}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*''[[The Gurkha's Daughter]]'', short story collection, released in December 2012.\n*''[[Land Where I Flee]]'', novel, released in December 2013.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parajuly, Prajwal}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Indian writers]]\n[[Category:Nepali-language writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Truman State University alumni]]