{"title_page": "Pyotr Lomako", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Pyotr Lomako<br>\u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0301\u043a\u043e\n| image         = Pyotr Lomako.jpg\n| office        = Chairman of [[Gosplan|State Planning Committee]]\n| predecessor   = [[Veniamin Dymshits]]\n| successor     = [[Nikolai Baibakov]]\n| term_start    = 24 November 1962\n| term_end      = 2 October 1965\n| 1blankname    = [[Deputy of Gosplan|Deputies]]\n| 1namedata     = [[Sergei Stepanov (politician)|Sergei Stepanov]]<br>[[Anatoly Korobov]]<br>[[Alexei Goreglyad]]<br>[[Nikolai Tikhonov]]\n|office3        = [[Ministry of Non-Ferrous Metallurgy|Minister Non-Ferrous Metallurgy]]\n|term_start3    = 2 October 1965\n|term_end3      = 31 October 1986\n|premier3       = [[Alexei Kosygin]]<br>[[Nikolai Tikhonov]]<br>[[Nikolai Ryzhkov]]\n|predecessor3   = None\u2014post established\n|successor3     = None\u2014post abolished\n|premier4       = [[Joseph Stalin]]<br>[[Georgy Malenkov]]<br>[[Nikolai Bulganin]]\n|term_start4    = 28 December 1950\n|term_end4      = 10 May 1957\n|predecessor4   = None\u2014post established\n|successor4     = None\u2014post abolished\n|premier5       = [[Joseph Stalin]]\n|term_start5    = 9 July 1940\n|term_end5      = 26 June 1948\n|predecessor5   = [[Alexander Samokhvalov (metallurgist)|Alexander Samokhvalov]]\n|successor5     = None\u2014post abolished\n| birth_place         = [[Temryuk]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| birth_date          = 12 July 1904\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1990|05|27|1904|07|12|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| party=[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] (1925-1989)}} \n'''Pyotr Fadeyevich Lomako''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u0424\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0301\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0301\u043a\u043e}}) (12 July 1904 &ndash; 27 May 1990) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[politician]] and [[economist]], head of [[Gosplan]] between 1962 and 1965. During the [[Second World War]], he was responsible for overseeing the evacuation of Soviet industry to the [[Ural mountains]] region.<ref>(in Russian) [http://www.hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html Biography at Khronos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028172921/http://hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html |date=2007-10-28 }}, accessed 7 July 2009.</ref> He was a seven-time recipient of the [[Order of Lenin]], and also received the golden medal of the [[Hero of Socialist Labor]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nPyotr Lomako was born to a family of peasant laborers on 12 July 1904 ([[Julian calendar|O.S.]]: 29 June) in [[Temryuk]], [[Krasnodar]].<ref>(in Russian) \"Lomako, Pyotr Fadeyevich\" in the ''[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]'', 3rd edition, Moscow 1972.</ref> He studied for three years at the [[Plekhanov Russian Academy of Economics|Plekhanov Institute of the National Economy]] before graduating in 1932 from the [[Moscow]] Institute of Nonferrous Metals and Gold. Between 1932 and 1939 he worked as an industrial manager: as a foreman, master, chief of shop, and then assistant to the chief engineer of a factory in [[Leningrad]], and then from 1937 as director of a nonferrous metals factory in the [[Ivanovo]] region.\n\n==Political career==\n\nLomako joined the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] in 1925. In 1939 he was made an assistant to the [[People's Commissar]] (Narkom) for Nonferrous Metallurgy, and in 1940 he was promoted to the post of Narkom. Lomako was a Deputy of the [[Supreme Soviet of the USSR]], being elected in the 2nd and the 4th through 8th elections to the body, serving between 1946 and 1950 and 1954 to 1989.\n\n===Second World War===\n\nAs an industrial Narkom, Lomako played an important role in maintaining Soviet industry after the outbreak of war in 1941. In particular, he was responsible for managing the mass evacuation of Soviet industry to the Ural mountains region.\n\n===Post-War===\n\nFollowing the Second World War, Lomako remained Narkom and subsequently [[Minister for Nonferrous Metallurgy]] until 1948. Between 1948 and 1950, he served as Deputy Minister for the [[Iron]] and [[Steel]] Industry. He was returned to original portfolio as a Minister in 1950, and then made Deputy Minister for Iron and Steel once again in 1951, before serving for a third time as Minister for Nonferrous Metallurgy between 1954 and 1957.\n\nIn 1957 Lomako left [[Sovmin]], becoming Chairman of the [[Krasnoyarsk]] People's Economic Council (Sovnarkhoz), a position he held until 1961.\n\n===Party career===\n\nLomako was a candidate member of the [[Central Committee of the CPSU]] at the [[19th Congress of the CPSU|19th]] and [[20th Congress of the CPSU|20th Congresses of the CPSU]]. At the [[22nd Congress of the CPSU]] in 1961, he was elected as a member, and became Vice-President of the [[RSFSR]] Bureau of the Committee, where he served until 1962.\n\nLomako was deselected from the Central Committee at the [[25th Congress of the CPSU|25th Party Congress]] in 1976.\n\n===Chairman of Gosplan===\n\nPyotr Lomako was selected to succeed [[Veniamin Dymshits]] as Chairman of [[Gosplan]], the State Planning Committee, on 24 November 1962. Lomako oversaw the transitional period between [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and [[Leonid Brezhnev]], and was therefore responsible for coordinating the Soviet economy at a time of economic uncertainty. As Lomako was also Deputy Chairman of [[Sovmin]] during this period, he fell under the direct influence of [[Alexei Kosygin]], the reformist Premier.\n\nLomako was responsible for coordinating a reformist economic policy, and is argued by contemporary Western analysts such as G. W. Simmonds to have been removed by Brezhnev in 1965 as part of a bid to weaken Kosygin's power and reintroduce economic conservatism.<ref>Simmonds, G. W. ''Soviet leaders''. New York 1967.</ref>\n\nAfter his removal from Gosplan, Lomako served as Minister for Non-Ferrous Metallurgy until 1985. He died in 1990 at the age of 85.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* (in Russian) \"Lomako, Pyotr Fadeyevich\" in the ''Great Soviet Encyclopedia'', 3rd edition, Moscow 1972.\n* (in Russian) [https://web.archive.org/web/20071028172921/http://hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html Biography at Khronos], accessed 7 July 2009\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n|title  = Chairman of the [[Gosplan|State Planning Committee]]\n|before = [[Veniamin Dymshits]]\n|after  = [[Nikolai Baibakov]]\n|years  = 1962&ndash;1965}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lomako, Pyotr}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Temryuksky District]]\n[[Category:People from Kuban Oblast]]\n[[Category:Soviet politicians]]\n[[Category:Russian economists]]\n[[Category:People's Commissars and Ministers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:Soviet economists]]\n[[Category:20th-century economists]]\n[[Category:Plekhanov Russian University of Economics alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Pyotr Lomako<br>\u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0301\u043a\u043e\n| image         = Pyotr Lomako.jpg\n| office        = Chairman of [[Gosplan|State Planning Committee]]\n| predecessor   = [[Veniamin Dymshits]]\n| successor     = [[Nikolai Baibakov]]\n| term_start    = 24 November 1962\n| term_end      = 2 October 1965\n| 1blankname    = [[Deputy of Gosplan|Deputies]]\n| 1namedata     = [[Sergei Stepanov (politician)|Sergei Stepanov]]<br>[[Anatoly Korobov]]<br>[[Alexei Goreglyad]]<br>[[Nikolai Tikhonov]]\n|office3        = [[Ministry of Non-Ferrous Metallurgy|Minister Non-Ferrous Metallurgy]]\n|term_start3    = 2 October 1965\n|term_end3      = 31 October 1986\n|premier3       = [[Alexei Kosygin]]<br>[[Nikolai Tikhonov]]<br>[[Nikolai Ryzhkov]]\n|predecessor3   = None\u2014post established\n|successor3     = None\u2014post abolished\n|premier4       = [[Joseph Stalin]]<br>[[Georgy Malenkov]]<br>[[Nikolai Bulganin]]\n|term_start4    = 28 December 1950\n|term_end4      = 10 May 1957\n|predecessor4   = None\u2014post established\n|successor4     = None\u2014post abolished\n|premier5       = [[Joseph Stalin]]\n|term_start5    = 9 July 1940\n|term_end5      = 26 June 1948\n|predecessor5   = [[Alexander Samokhvalov (metallurgist)|Alexander Samokhvalov]]\n|successor5     = None\u2014post abolished\n| birth_place         = [[Temryuk]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| birth_date          = 12 July 1904\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1990|05|27|1904|07|12|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| party=[[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]}} (1925-1989)\n'''Pyotr Fadeyevich Lomako''' ({{Lang-ru|\u041f\u0451\u0442\u0440 \u0424\u0430\u0434\u0435\u0301\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041b\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0301\u043a\u043e}}) (12 July 1904 &ndash; 27 May 1990) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[politician]] and [[economist]], head of [[Gosplan]] between 1962 and 1965. During the [[Second World War]], he was responsible for overseeing the evacuation of Soviet industry to the [[Ural mountains]] region.<ref>(in Russian) [http://www.hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html Biography at Khronos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028172921/http://hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html |date=2007-10-28 }}, accessed 7 July 2009.</ref> He was a seven-time recipient of the [[Order of Lenin]], and also received the golden medal of the [[Hero of Socialist Labor]].\n\n==Early life==\n\nPyotr Lomako was born to a family of peasant laborers on 12 July 1904 ([[Julian calendar|O.S.]]: 29 June) in [[Temryuk]], [[Krasnodar]].<ref>(in Russian) \"Lomako, Pyotr Fadeyevich\" in the ''[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]'', 3rd edition, Moscow 1972.</ref> He studied for three years at the [[Plekhanov Russian Academy of Economics|Plekhanov Institute of the National Economy]] before graduating in 1932 from the [[Moscow]] Institute of Nonferrous Metals and Gold. Between 1932 and 1939 he worked as an industrial manager: as a foreman, master, chief of shop, and then assistant to the chief engineer of a factory in [[Leningrad]], and then from 1937 as director of a nonferrous metals factory in the [[Ivanovo]] region.\n\n==Political career==\n\nLomako joined the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist Party]] in 1925. In 1939 he was made an assistant to the [[People's Commissar]] (Narkom) for Nonferrous Metallurgy, and in 1940 he was promoted to the post of Narkom. Lomako was a Deputy of the [[Supreme Soviet of the USSR]], being elected in the 2nd and the 4th through 8th elections to the body, serving between 1946 and 1950 and 1954 to 1989.\n\n===Second World War===\n\nAs an industrial Narkom, Lomako played an important role in maintaining Soviet industry after the outbreak of war in 1941. In particular, he was responsible for managing the mass evacuation of Soviet industry to the Ural mountains region.\n\n===Post-War===\n\nFollowing the Second World War, Lomako remained Narkom and subsequently [[Minister for Nonferrous Metallurgy]] until 1948. Between 1948 and 1950, he served as Deputy Minister for the [[Iron]] and [[Steel]] Industry. He was returned to original portfolio as a Minister in 1950, and then made Deputy Minister for Iron and Steel once again in 1951, before serving for a third time as Minister for Nonferrous Metallurgy between 1954 and 1957.\n\nIn 1957 Lomako left [[Sovmin]], becoming Chairman of the [[Krasnoyarsk]] People's Economic Council (Sovnarkhoz), a position he held until 1961.\n\n===Party career===\n\nLomako was a candidate member of the [[Central Committee of the CPSU]] at the [[19th Congress of the CPSU|19th]] and [[20th Congress of the CPSU|20th Congresses of the CPSU]]. At the [[22nd Congress of the CPSU]] in 1961, he was elected as a member, and became Vice-President of the [[RSFSR]] Bureau of the Committee, where he served until 1962.\n\nLomako was deselected from the Central Committee at the [[25th Congress of the CPSU|25th Party Congress]] in 1976.\n\n===Chairman of Gosplan===\n\nPyotr Lomako was selected to succeed [[Veniamin Dymshits]] as Chairman of [[Gosplan]], the State Planning Committee, on 24 November 1962. Lomako oversaw the transitional period between [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and [[Leonid Brezhnev]], and was therefore responsible for coordinating the Soviet economy at a time of economic uncertainty. As Lomako was also Deputy Chairman of [[Sovmin]] during this period, he fell under the direct influence of [[Alexei Kosygin]], the reformist Premier.\n\nLomako was responsible for coordinating a reformist economic policy, and is argued by contemporary Western analysts such as G. W. Simmonds to have been removed by Brezhnev in 1965 as part of a bid to weaken Kosygin's power and reintroduce economic conservatism.<ref>Simmonds, G. W. ''Soviet leaders''. New York 1967.</ref>\n\nAfter his removal from Gosplan, Lomako served as Minister for Non-Ferrous Metallurgy until 1985. He died in 1990 at the age of 85.\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* (in Russian) \"Lomako, Pyotr Fadeyevich\" in the ''Great Soviet Encyclopedia'', 3rd edition, Moscow 1972.\n* (in Russian) [https://web.archive.org/web/20071028172921/http://hronos.km.ru/biograf/lomako.html Biography at Khronos], accessed 7 July 2009\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box\n|title  = Chairman of the [[Gosplan|State Planning Committee]]\n|before = [[Veniamin Dymshits]]\n|after  = [[Nikolai Baibakov]]\n|years  = 1962&ndash;1965}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lomako, Pyotr}}\n[[Category:1904 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Temryuksky District]]\n[[Category:People from Kuban Oblast]]\n[[Category:Soviet politicians]]\n[[Category:Russian economists]]\n[[Category:People's Commissars and Ministers of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union members]]\n[[Category:Soviet 